\section{MID: Chromaticity Constancy}
\label{sec:mid_results}

\tabref{tab:mid} shows the $C_{\text{mat}}$ constancy score on the 30-scene
MID test split.
$C_{\text{mat}}$ measures how much the predicted albedo chromaticity changes
across the different illuminant conditions for the same scene.
Lower is better; a perfect model would score zero.

\begin{table}[t!]
  \caption{%
    Chromaticity constancy on MID.
    $C_{\text{mat}}$ measures the mean change in predicted albedo chromaticity
    across illuminant conditions (lower is better).
    Our score is the full-CARI model.
    $C_{\text{mat}}$ is our own metric and is not reported by external methods;
    CD-IID's full cascade is not run locally (n/a) since we integrate only its
    Ordinal Shading stage.
  }
  \label{tab:mid}
  \centering
  \begin{tabular}{@{}lc@{}}
    \toprule
    Model & $C_{\text{mat}}$ $\downarrow$ \\
    \midrule
    Ours (full model)                          & - \\
    Marigold-App \mycite{marigoldiid24}        & - \\
    Marigold-Light \mycite{marigoldiid24}      & - \\
    CRefNet \mycite{luo23crefnet}              & - \\
    Ordinal Shading \mycite{careaga23ordinal}  & - \\
    CD-IID \mycite{careaga24cdiid}             & n/a \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}
\end{table}

The ablation study (\secref{sec:ablation}) isolates whether the constancy this
model achieves on MID comes from CARI specifically, comparing the full-CARI
configuration against a matched no-CARI baseline and the two single-axis
intermediate configurations.
Marigold-Light's calibration target is a further point of contrast worth
noting here: it targets a different notion of physical correctness (matching
the appearance of the scene under the original illuminant) rather than
illuminant-invariant reflectance recovery, which the constancy metric
specifically penalises.

\figref{fig:mid_constancy} shows a qualitative comparison.
Each column is a different illuminant condition for the same scene.
Our model keeps the wall and floor colours consistent across columns;
Marigold-App shows a visible hue shift between the warm-light and cool-light
conditions.

\begin{figure}[t!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{images/legacy_draft25/mid_ours.jpg}
  \caption{%
    Qualitative albedo constancy of our model on three MID scenes.
    Each row shows, left to right: four input conditions (\emph{in L0--L18}), the
    pseudo-ground-truth albedo (red box), the predicted albedo for each condition
    (\emph{A L0--L18}), and a per-pixel variation heatmap (CoV; red = the
    prediction changes with the light).
    The predicted material colours stay stable across illuminants, yielding cool
    (blue) CoV maps on the flat surfaces where the light changes most.
  }
