\end{figure}


\section{ARAP: Constancy, Cast, and Structure}
\label{sec:arap_results}

ARAP is evaluated under two different input conditions, because the standard
protocol and the axis this thesis targets require different inputs.
The standard protocol white-balances the input --- desaturating the shading
layer before it multiplies back into the image --- which removes the
colour-illuminant signal entirely and is the convention \mycite{careaga23ordinal}
and \mycite{careaga24cdiid} use for their published numbers.
Reporting our numbers under that same condition (\tabref{tab:arap_standard})
makes them directly comparable to the published values, but it cannot exercise
colour constancy, since the input no longer carries a colour cast to be
constant \emph{about}.
The thesis claim instead needs the raw, coloured input preserved
(\tabref{tab:arap_thesis}); no published work reports scores under this
condition, so every row there is run locally.

