\end{table}

\paragraph{On the reliability of WHDR}
Before drawing strong conclusions from these numbers, it is worth stressing that
WHDR is a weak metric.
It is computed from sparse human judgements of \emph{relative} lightness between
pairs of points, so it is subjective, evaluates ordering only, and ignores
absolute albedo and hue entirely \mycite{sato25metrics}.
These limitations are documented: methods that improve WHDR frequently do poorly
on objective intensity and chromaticity metrics \mycite{sato25metrics}, which is
exactly the gap the MAW benchmark was created to close \mycite{maw}.
We therefore read WHDR as indicative, not decisive, and weigh it against the
objective accuracy axes reported in \tabref{tab:arap_standard} and
\tabref{tab:maw} rather than on its own.

\figref{fig:iiw} shows qualitative results on the IIW test set.

\begin{figure}[t!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{images/legacy_draft25/iiw_ours.jpg}
  \caption{%
    Qualitative albedo predictions from our model on IIW test images.
    Each row shows an input image (left) and its predicted albedo (right).
    The predicted albedos are smooth and consistent in colour (good for
    constancy) but lack the sharp shadow boundaries that human annotators
    associate with good albedo recovery (which would improve WHDR); note also
    the residual shading on the ceiling and around the windows, which the
    diffuse model does not fully absorb.
  }
  \label{fig:iiw}
\end{figure}


\section{Ablation Study}
\label{sec:ablation}

The benchmark sections placed our model against external methods.
We now turn inward with two controlled studies that together justify the design.
The first --- the \emph{CARI ablation} of this section --- asks whether the
constancy our model achieves genuinely comes from CARI, or from something
incidental; it isolates the two CARI components in a $2\times2$ ablation.
The second --- the \emph{fine-tuning lever sweep} of \secref{sec:lever_sweep} ---
takes the resulting full-CARI model and asks whether short, targeted fine-tuning
can improve it further.
The two studies share a single logic --- change one thing at a time against a
matched control --- and together they explain both \emph{why} the model is built
the way it is and \emph{what} the cheaper alternatives cost.

The ablation isolates the contribution of CARI by comparing
configurations along two axes: whether the cross-render losses
($\mathcal{L}_{\text{inv}}$, $\mathcal{L}_{\text{expl}}$) are active, and
whether the wide RGB colour skip into the albedo head is active
(\secref{sec:architecture}) — the two components that, per the coupling
argument in \secref{sec:architecture}, are expected to interact.
\tabref{tab:ablation} summarises the resulting $2 \times 2$ design, split into
two parts: Part~1 reports self-consistency (constancy) across illuminant
conditions on the raw-coloured input — the axis the thesis claims to improve
— and Part~2 reports accuracy against ground truth, including a white-balanced
multi-light ARAP accuracy guard. The latter supports the within-study comparison
but is not used as a reproduced published score.
All four configurations share the same 19k initialization, data curriculum,
and 40k training horizon. The two within-architecture comparisons are the
causal CARI tests: Row~1$\rightarrow$Row~2 toggles cross-render losses with
the colour skip off, and Row~3$\rightarrow$Row~4 does the same with the
colour skip on. Changing the colour skip also changes the head parameter set;
the corresponding fresh-optimizer fallback means cross-skip comparisons are
descriptive rather than a standalone causal estimate. The table therefore
separates the clean cross-render result from the observed full-configuration
trade-off instead of attributing every row difference to one switch.

\begin{table}[t!]
  \caption{%
    Ablation isolating the two axes of CARI: cross-render losses and the wide
    colour-skip connection.
    All configurations share the same 19k initialization, data curriculum, and
    40k horizon. Row~1$\rightarrow$Row~2 and Row~3$\rightarrow$Row~4 are the
    matched cross-render comparisons; colour-skip contrasts are descriptive
    because the changed head parameter set takes a fresh optimizer path.
    Part~1 reports self-consistency across illuminants on the raw-coloured
    input; Part~2 reports accuracy against ground truth, with ARAP under the
    white-balanced multi-light ARAP subset (marked $\dagger$) as an internal
    accuracy guard; it is not presented as a reproduced published score.
    Lower is better on every column except ARAP SSIM; best per column is
    \textbf{bold} (ties at displayed precision are both bolded).
    Figure~\ref{fig:ablation} shows the corresponding albedo and the
    luminance- and chroma-cast CoV heatmaps for each row.
  }
  \label{tab:ablation}
  \centering
  \textbf{\small Part 1: Constancy (self-consistency across illuminants)}\\[3pt]
  \resizebox{\textwidth}{!}{%
  \begin{tabular}{@{}lllcccc@{}}
    \toprule
