        & ARAP SSIM$^\dagger$ $\uparrow$ & IIW WHDR $\downarrow$ \\
    \midrule
    1 & 4.434 & 0.409 & 0.028 & 0.229 & 0.843 & 0.334 \\
    2 & 4.631 & 0.474 & 0.028 & 0.213 & \textbf{0.845} & \textbf{0.283} \\
    3 & \textbf{4.115} & \textbf{0.395} & 0.026 & 0.221 & 0.842 & 0.327 \\
    4 & 4.155 & 0.504 & \textbf{0.025} & \textbf{0.209} & \textbf{0.845} & 0.286 \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}}\\[4pt]
  {\footnotesize $\dagger$ white-balanced multi-light ARAP subset (31 groups);
  an internal accuracy guard, not a direct reproduction of a published ARAP table.
  IIW WHDR is ancillary and is not used for model selection.}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Effect of cross-render losses within each architecture}
The clean CARI comparisons are Row~1$\rightarrow$Row~2 and
Row~3$\rightarrow$Row~4. With the colour skip off, cross-render losses improve
three of the four raw-coloured constancy columns: MID $C_{\text{mat}}$
falls from 0.250 to 0.180, ARAP $C_{\text{arap}}$ from 0.108 to 0.097,
and ARAP $\text{Cast}_{\text{RMS}}$ from 0.060 to 0.049. They also improve
the ancillary IIW WHDR from 0.334 to 0.283, while both MAW measures worsen.
With the colour skip on, adding cross-render losses produces the strongest
luminance and structural result: MID $C_{\text{mat}}$ falls from 0.259 to
0.157 and the white-balanced ARAP guard improves on LMSE (0.026 to 0.025) and
si-RMSE (0.221 to 0.209). The same comparison worsens MID chroma-cast
variation (0.519 to 0.555) and both MAW measures. Thus cross-render losses
reliably improve the luminance-oriented and ARAP-structure axes here, but do
not remove the chroma-accuracy trade-off introduced by the wide colour path.

\paragraph{Observed colour-skip trade-off}
Rows that differ in colour skip also differ in optimizer initialization, so
Rows~1/3 and Rows~2/4 are not used as causal estimates of that architectural
choice. Descriptively, the colour-skip rows are strongest on absolute MAW
colour: Row~3 obtains the best $\Delta E$ (4.115) and intensity score
(0.395). Row~4 is the strongest accuracy-focused full configuration, winning
MID $C_{\text{mat}}$ and the two white-balanced ARAP error columns, but it
is the weakest row on MID $\text{Cast}_{\text{RMS}}$ (0.555) and MAW
intensity (0.504). This is the measured trade-off carried into the subsequent
fine-tuning study, not a claim that one Table-A row dominates every criterion.

\paragraph{Role of IIW and ARAP in the next study}
IIW WHDR is a sparse, subjective ordinal measure; it is therefore retained as
an ancillary column rather than a selection criterion. Its Row~2 result is
consistent with the real cross-render signal helping ordinal reflectance, but
does not establish that transfer on its own. ARAP varies less across the four
rows than MID: $C_{\text{arap}}$ spans 0.097--0.108 and
$\text{Cast}_{\text{RMS}}$ 0.049--0.061, whereas the corresponding MID
ranges are 0.157--0.259 and 0.268--0.555. This limited ARAP response motivates
testing a synthetic cross-render source in the next ablation; it is a
hypothesis motivated by the measured domain difference, not a conclusion about
its cause.

\paragraph{Why Row 4 initializes Table B}
Row~4 is used as the Table-B starting point because it is the complete CARI
configuration and has the best measured MID luminance constancy and
white-balanced ARAP error scores among the four rows. This is a practical base
choice, not an assertion that it wins MAW or chroma-cast stability: those
weaknesses remain explicit in \tabref{tab:ablation} and are central to the
next study's ARAP--MAW selection criteria.

\figref{fig:ablation} shows the qualitative effect of each ablation row.

\begin{figure}[t!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{images/tableA_40k/ablation_mid.jpg}
  \caption{%
    Ablation: the four CARI configurations on one MID scene under three
    illuminant conditions (L0, L10, L20).
    Columns: the three input conditions, the pseudo-ground-truth albedo (red
    box), the three predicted albedos, and two cross-condition variation
    heatmaps computed across five illuminant conditions (L0--L20 in steps of
    5, three of which are shown) --- luminance CoV, matching MID
    $C_{\text{mat}}$, and chroma-cast CoV, matching MID
    $\text{Cast}_{\text{RMS}}$ ($\sqrt{\mathrm{Var}(R/G) + \mathrm{Var}(B/G)}$
    across conditions).
    Rows, top to bottom: no CARI (Row~1), cross-render only (Row~2), colour-skip
    only (Row~3), and full CARI (Row~4).
    These are local, single-scene illustrations rather than estimates of the
    full-split metrics in \tabref{tab:ablation}: the heatmaps expose where the
    predicted albedo changes with illumination, while the table establishes the
    dataset-level ranking. In particular, chroma variation is spatially and
    scene dependent, so the figure is not used to infer the global
    $\text{Cast}_{\text{RMS}}$ ordering.
  }
  \label{fig:ablation}
\end{figure}


\section{Controlled Negative Results}
\label{sec:negative_results}

Two further studies, run as controlled comparisons rather than as attempts to
maximise a benchmark score, are reported here precisely because their outcome
is negative: they rule out a plausible alternative design and an
over-engineered training lever, and both support the same lesson — the
disambiguating \emph{signal} (real cross-illuminant pairs) is what does the
work, not the specific architecture or an elaborate loss built on top of it.

\subsection{An Alternative Shading-First Architecture}
\label{sec:v20_negative}

An apparently natural alternative to CARI is to make the illuminant estimate
\emph{explicit} rather than implicit: predict a grey shading intensity field
and a separate low-resolution illuminant-colour field, then derive the albedo
\emph{analytically} as $\mathbf{A} = \mathbf{I} / \mathbf{S}$, instead of
predicting albedo directly and constraining it with CARI.
We built and trained this shading-first architecture to a comparable training
budget.
An initial version collapsed during training (the analytic division leaves the
absolute scale of the shading an unconstrained free parameter, which a
component of the loss could exploit to drive shading to zero and albedo to
white); after a set of stabilising fixes — an explicit absolute-scale anchor,
a diffuse-reconstruction term gated to avoid re-introducing the same free
parameter, and a soft-clamped division — the architecture trained stably to
completion.

A stable shading-first model, however, still loses to our directly-predicted,
CARI-constrained albedo on every constancy metric we measured, under an
identical evaluation for both models:

\begin{table}[h!]
  \caption{%
    Alternative shading-first architecture versus our directly-predicted,
    CARI-constrained albedo, evaluated identically for both models on MID and
    the indoor ARAP groups (11 of which are the coloured-illuminant subset).
    All columns are constancy or accuracy metrics (lower is better).
    The alternative architecture loses on every column.
  }
  \label{tab:v20_negative}
  \centering
  \resizebox{\textwidth}{!}{%
  \begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
    \toprule
    & MID $C_{\text{mat}}$ $\downarrow$ & ARAP $C_{\text{arap}}$ $\downarrow$
    & ARAP $C_{\text{arap}}$ (coloured) $\downarrow$ \\
    \midrule
    Alternative (shading-first)     & 0.275 & 0.247 & 0.335 \\
    \textbf{Ours (direct + CARI)}   & \textbf{0.177} & \textbf{0.123} & \textbf{0.149} \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}}
\end{table}

The reason is instructive: the analytic division $\mathbf{A} = \mathbf{I}/\mathbf{S}$
gives shading intensity and shading colour a direct, unconstrained path back
into the albedo whenever the shading prediction is imperfect, and no amount of
architectural stabilisation removes that path.
Directly predicting albedo and constraining it with a cross-illuminant
invariance loss pins both far more effectively, because the constraint acts on
the quantity that must stay constant, rather than on an intermediate quantity
one division step away from it.
We take this as evidence for the central design choice of this thesis: the
value is in the cross-illuminant \emph{signal} and how it constrains the
prediction, not in a more elaborate decomposition head.

\subsection{Fine-Tuning Lever Sweep}
\label{sec:lever_sweep}

The ablation established that CARI works; this study asks the natural follow-up
question --- can the full-CARI model be pushed further?
The idea is targeted fine-tuning: rather than change the architecture, we add one
extra loss term at a time, each aimed at a specific residual weakness observed
qualitatively in the full-CARI output (\figref{fig:iiw}, \figref{fig:levers}).
Two weaknesses stand out: smooth shading ramps that survive in the albedo on
flat surfaces, and shadow boundaries that leak into the albedo.
The flatness and shadow-based levers below target exactly these, and the ordinal
lever targets shading order directly.
We evaluate five such levers, each fine-tuned from the
full-CARI base checkpoint (at 50k iterations, \secref{sec:schedule}) for a
further 10k iterations --- to 60k total --- under the same data mix and
learning-rate schedule, alongside a zero-lever control fine-tuned for the
identical 10k iterations.
The control isolates the effect of the extra training itself, so that each
lever is measured relative to it rather than to the base — a pre-registered
no-regression gate keeps a lever only if it does not regress the
coloured-illuminant constancy metrics or the albedo-accuracy guard by more than
approximately 10\% relative to the control.
Writing $\mathbf{A}$ and $\mathbf{S}_d$ for the predicted albedo and diffuse
shading and $\mathbf{I}$ for the input, the five levers are defined as follows.
The synthetic relighting used by the shadow-based levers is shown in
\figref{fig:shadow_aug}. This branch is separate from CARI: CARI's
$\mathcal{L}_{\text{inv}}$ uses real MID raw pairs, while the shadow branch
manufactures a second observation on Hypersim and applies only the
$\mathcal{L}_{\text{sh\_inv}}$ and $\mathcal{L}_{\text{sh\_explain}}$ terms.

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Flatness} (\emph{flat}) — a chroma-gated low-frequency
        albedo-flatness prior. With $\mathbf{A}_{\text{LF}}$ a low-pass of the
        predicted albedo and $w_c$ a per-pixel gate that is high only where the
        local chromaticity is uniform (same material),
        $\mathcal{L}_{\text{flat}} = \sum_p w_c(p)\,\lVert \nabla
        \mathbf{A}_{\text{LF}}(p) \rVert_1$.
        It removes smooth shading ramps left in the albedo while the chroma
        gate preserves genuine material and texture edges.
  \item \textbf{Shadow-invariance} (\emph{sh\_inv}) — a manufactured-shadow
        self-supervision. A smooth synthetic relighting field $\sigma$ is cast
        onto a Hypersim image, and the predicted albedo is required to be
        invariant to it:
        $\mathcal{L}_{\text{sh\_inv}} = \lVert \mathbf{A}(\mathbf{I} \odot
        \sigma) - \mathbf{A}(\mathbf{I}) \rVert_1$.
  \item \textbf{Flatness + shadow-invariance} (\emph{flat\,+\,sh\_inv}) — both
        terms active together.
  \item \textbf{Shadow-invariance + shadow-explain} (\emph{sh\_inv\,+\,sh\_explain})
        — the shadow term augmented with an explain companion that requires the
        \emph{shading} to absorb the synthetic change, mirroring the structure
        of $\mathcal{L}_{\text{expl}}$:
        $\mathcal{L}_{\text{sh\_explain}} = \lVert \log \mathbf{S}_d(\mathbf{I}
        \odot \sigma) - \log \mathbf{S}_d(\mathbf{I}) - \log \sigma \rVert_1$.
  \item \textbf{Ordinal shading} (\emph{ordinal}) — an order-based supervision
        on the predicted shading against the Hypersim ground-truth shading. For
        random pixel pairs $(p,q)$ it applies a hinge on the sign of the shading
        difference, $\sum_{(p,q)} \max\!\big(0,\, m - \operatorname{sign}(
        S^\star_p - S^\star_q)\,(S_p - S_q)\big)$ with margin $m$, following the
        ordinal-shading formulation of \mycite{careaga23ordinal}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[t!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{images/legacy_draft25/shadow_aug.jpg}
  \caption{%
    Synthetic relighting used by the shadow-based fine-tuning levers.
    A known multiplicative field is applied to a Hypersim image to manufacture a
    shadowed or sunlit second observation.
    $\mathcal{L}_{\text{sh\_inv}}$ requires the albedo to stay invariant under
    this manufactured relighting, while $\mathcal{L}_{\text{sh\_explain}}$
    requires the predicted shading to absorb the known field.
    These losses are distinct from CARI's real-pair invariance loss.
  }
  \label{fig:shadow_aug}
\end{figure}

\tabref{tab:lever_sweep} reports the sweep and \figref{fig:levers} shows the
resulting albedo for each lever: two levers pass the gate cleanly, one is mixed,
and two fail on every axis.

\begin{table}[h!]
  \caption{%
    Fine-tuning lever sweep versus a zero-lever control fine-tuned under the
    identical matched-schedule recipe. All columns are lower-is-better;
    ``(fail)'' marks a regression beyond the pre-registered no-regression gate.
  }
  \label{tab:lever_sweep}
  \centering
  \resizebox{\textwidth}{!}{%
  \begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
    \toprule
    Fine-tuning lever & ARAP $C_{\text{arap}}$ (coloured) $\downarrow$ & MID $C_{\text{mat}}$ $\downarrow$
    & IIW WHDR $\downarrow$ \\
    \midrule
    Zero-lever control              & - & - & - \\
    flat                            & - & - & - \\
    sh\_inv                         & - & - & - \\
    flat + sh\_inv                  & - & - & - \\
    sh\_inv + sh\_explain           & - & - & - \\
    ordinal                         & - & - & - \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}}
\end{table}

Each lever is read against the zero-lever control rather than against the base
checkpoint, isolating the effect of the extra loss term from the effect of the
extra fine-tuning steps themselves.
The pre-registered gate (\secref{sec:lever_sweep}, above) keeps a lever only if
it does not regress the coloured-illuminant constancy metrics or the
albedo-accuracy guard by more than approximately 10\% relative to the control;
\figref{fig:levers} shows the predicted albedo for every row so the gate
outcome can be read qualitatively alongside the table.

\begin{figure}[t!]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{images/legacy_draft25/levers.jpg}
  \caption{%
    Predicted albedo of each fine-tuning lever, shown on one scene from each of
    three benchmarks (MID, MAW, IIW; one per row).
    The first column is the reference: the ground-truth albedo (red box) for MID
    and MAW, and the input photograph for IIW.
    The passing levers (\emph{flat}, \emph{flat\,+\,sh\_inv}) keep material
    colour and contrast across all three; the failing levers
    (\emph{sh\_inv\,+\,sh\_explain}, \emph{ordinal}) produce a flatter,
    over-desaturated albedo.
  }
